						<p><div class="item">
<h2><a class="listing" style="link" href="/en/Dossiers/CTA-and-S-T/Developments/Africa-should-lead-CDM-Kenyan-minister-tells-climate-change-delegates" title="Africa should lead CDM, Kenyan minister tells climate change delegates" alt="link">Africa should lead CDM, Kenyan minister tells climate change delegates</a></h2>

	
					<p> The CDM in Africa should be African-led programme, focused on real projects in partnership with local institutions, said David Mwiraria, Kenya’s environment minister. Progress to kick-start the CDM in Africa has been slow.’ Work is still needed to ensure Africa plays a big role in the project tangible results are to be realized,’ he said. ‘Local institutions should play a big role in the projects.’ Mwiraria called on all parties to the climate change convention to recognize that the challenge of framing of future climate regime is extremely urgent. Out of more than 850 CDM projects now being implemented worldwide, only 23 (2.6%) are in Africa. UNDP, UNEP, the World Bank, African Development Bank and the UN Convention on Climate Change (UNFCCC) secretariat have joined forces to write a project proposal, and are now seeking donor support. The first outcome is a joint UNEP six-country CDM capacity development project managed by the UNDP in Addis Ababa, which covers Ethiopia, Kenya, Mauritius, Mozambique, Tanzania and Zambia, and was launched in October. ‘In Africa, efforts to capture CDM benefits are accelerating, supported by a number of individual and joint UN efforts. Overcoming the complexity of the CDM and general investment barriers cannot be done overnight, but our sustained efforts are producing results,’ John Christensen, head of UNEP Risø Centre in Denmark. Source: Africa Science News Service, 7 December 2007.</p>
							<p><span class="date">7/01/2008</span></p>
	<div class="cnt">
	<a class="link" href="/en/Dossiers/CTA-and-S-T/Developments/Africa-should-lead-CDM-Kenyan-minister-tells-climate-change-delegates">Read more...</a>
</div>
<br class="cl">
